INSURABLE INTEREST

WASHINGTON The Supreme
Court said it will hold fast hear
ings in effort to reopen closed
public schools in Prince Edward
County, Virginia, next fall on an
integrated basis.


Public schools have been
closed since 1859 because of the
desegregation ruling. County
funds we're used to establish
private all white schools while
Negro pupils have been without
facilities.


The court unanimously upheld
a decision striking down Loui-
siana law which requires race
segregation at public athletic
contests and other entertain
mentS.

SUPREME COURT


HEARS RACE CASES

An assistant professor of his
tory at Princeton University has
penned a new play, which is being
shown at the Sheridan Square
Playhouse in New York City.


Martin Duberman, SO, scholar
and researcher, wrote, lin White
America" an adaptation of docu-
ments concerned with the history
of the Negro in the United States.


The drama is enacted with six
performers and a guitarist. The
sentiments of great Americans
including Thomas Jefferson and
Woodrow Wilson, on the future of
the Negro in America.


Gloria Foster and Michael O
Sullivan have leading roles In
the drama.

HOT SPRINGS. Ark. = Arson
is the suspected cause of a
$500, 900 fire which Quilted the
church pastored by the president
of the local branch of the Ma
tional Association for the Ad-
vancement of Colored People.


Report of a private investiga-
ton initiated by trustees of the
historic Roanoke Baptist Church,
Wilmington Avenue at Ozark
Street, indicates that the blaze
that destroyed the interior of
the edifice, Sunday, December %
was intentionally started.


The Rev. James Donald Rice
is pastor of the 95-year old
church. The minister s militant
efforts in his capacity as NAACP
head, in winning civil rights VIC
tories in the area has made him
the target of numerous threats
upon his life and those of his
family - the latest coming the
night before the fire.
